      {
        "category": "technology_constraint",
        "boundary": "Angular 19 will drop the legacy SASS compiler; the project must adopt the new builder to stay compatible with the upcoming framework version.",
        "severity": "blocking",
        "source_facts": ["tech_versions.json: Angular 18-lts", "ADR: UVZ-09-ADR-003 Frontend Build Strategy SASS Import Deprecation"]
      },
      {
        "category": "dependency_risk",
        "boundary": "The new @angular-devkit/build-angular:application brings its own SASS version. All @angular/* packages must be upgraded in lockstep to avoid version mismatches.",
        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": ["dependencies.json: @angular/core v18-lts", "dependencies.json: @angular/compiler v18-lts"]
      },
      {
        "category": "testing_constraint",
        "boundary": "After changing the builder, existing Karma unit tests and Playwright e2e tests must be executed to catch regressions caused by SASS compilation differences.",
        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": ["tech_versions.json: Karma 6.4.3", "tech_versions.json: Playwright 1.44.1"]
      },
      {
        "category": "workflow_constraint",
        "boundary": "CI pipelines that invoke \"ng build\" will need to reference the new builder target; scripts or Docker images that pin the old builder may fail.",
        "severity": "info",
        "source_facts": ["tech_versions.json: Gradle 8.2.1 (used for CI orchestration)"]
      }
    ],
    "architecture_notes": "WALKTHROUGH: The change lives entirely in the **presentation container** (the Angular SPA). Within that container, it touches the **presentation layer** (build configuration, SASS assets). The primary component is the **Angular Build Configuration** (angular.json) which is consumed by the **CI Build Job** (infrastructure container) during the pipeline. Downstream, the **Karma unit test runner** and **Playwright e2e runner** consume the compiled assets, so they are neighboring components that must be re‑run after migration. No other containers (e.g., domain, data‑access, infrastructure services) are impacted.",
    "anticipated_questions": [
      {
        "question": "Do we need to upgrade the whole Angular framework to version 19 now, or only the SASS builder?",
        "answer": "Only the builder needs to be switched to @angular-devkit/build-angular:application for the migration. The full Angular 19 upgrade can be performed later, but the builder change must happen now to avoid future incompatibility."
      },
      {
        "question": "Will any existing .scss files need to be rewritten?",
        "answer": "The new compiler deprecates certain import syntaxes (e.g., tilde‑based imports). Review the ADR for the exact deprecations; most files will work unchanged, but any usage of the old import style must be updated."
      },
      {
        "question": "How will this affect our CI/CD pipeline?",
        "answer": "The pipeline step that runs \"ng build\" must reference the new builder target. Verify that the Docker image or Node version used in CI supports the newer @angular-devkit version."
      },
      {
        "question": "Are there any known breaking changes that could cause test failures?",
        "answer": "The SASS compiler may produce slightly different CSS output, which can affect visual regression tests. Run the full Karma and Playwright suites after migration to catch any discrepancies."
      },
      {
        "question": "Is there a fallback if the migration introduces issues?",
        "answer": "You can temporarily revert the angular.json change and continue using the legacy builder on Angular 18, but this will postpone the required upgrade and must be addressed before the Angular 19 release."
      }
    ],
    "linked_tasks": [
      "UVZUSLNVV-5890 (Angular 19 upgrade planning)",
      "UVZ-09-ADR-003 (Frontend Build Strategy SASS Import Deprecation)"
    ]
  }
